{"questionId":"3396576","questionHtml":"<p>An atom of hydrogen (<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mmultiscripts><mtext>H</mtext><mprescripts></mprescripts><mn>1</mn><mn>1</mn></mmultiscripts></math>) and an atom of helium (<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mmultiscripts><mtext>He</mtext><mprescripts></mprescripts><mn>2</mn><mn>4</mn></mmultiscripts></math>) are moving with the same kinetic energy.</p>\n<p>The de Broglie wavelength of the hydrogen atom is&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>λ</mi><mtext>H</mtext></msub></math> and the de Broglie wavelength of the helium atom is <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>λ</mi><mtext>He</mtext></msub></math>.</p>\n<p>What is <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><msub><mi>λ</mi><mtext>H</mtext></msub><msub><mi>λ</mi><mtext>He</mtext></msub></mfrac></math>?</p>\n<p><br>A.&nbsp;&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac></math></p>\n<p>B.&nbsp; <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>1</mn></math></p>\n<p>C.&nbsp; <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>2</mn></math></p>\n<p>D.&nbsp; <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>4</mn></math></p>","markschemeHtml":"<p>C</p>","meta":{"questionId":"3396576","referenceCode":"EXE.1A.HL.TZ0.29","subjectId":"59-dp-physics-first-assessment-2025","title":"An atom of hydrogen (H11) and an atom of helium (He24) are moving with the same kinetic energy. The de Broglie wavelength of the hydrogen atom is λH and the de Broglie wavelength o","paper":"1A","level":"HL","questionNumber":"29","marksAvailable":"[Maximum mark: 1]","breadcrumbLabels":["E. Nuclear and quantum physics","E. Nuclear and quantum physics","E.2 Quantum physics"],"memberSectionIds":[],"sectionOrders":{}},"schemaVersion":2}